Quality of Service (QoS) in MQTT defines the level of guarantee that a message will be delivered between the publisher and the subscriber.
MQTT provides three QoS levels.
| QoS Level                 | Description                                                                                                          | Reliability | Use Case                                                                                       |
| ------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **QoS 0 – At most once**  | The message is sent only once with no acknowledgment. If it is lost, it is not retransmitted.                        | Lowest      | Sensor data where occasional data loss is acceptable (e.g., room temperature).                 |
| **QoS 1 – At least once** | The sender retransmits the message until it receives an acknowledgment. The receiver may receive duplicate messages. | Medium      | Water level monitoring, environmental sensors, and smart agriculture.                          |
| **QoS 2 – Exactly once**  | The message is delivered exactly once using a four-step handshake, preventing duplicates.                            | Highest     | Banking, payment systems, and industrial automation where duplicate messages are unacceptable. |
For an IoT water level monitoring system, QoS 1 (At least once) is the best choice.

Reason:

Ensures important water level alerts are delivered reliably.
If a message is lost, MQTT automatically retransmits it until an acknowledgment is received.
Occasional duplicate messages are acceptable because the application can ignore repeated readings.
It provides a good balance between reliability, network bandwidth, and power consumption.
QoS 2 offers higher reliability but introduces additional communication overhead, making it less efficient for most sensor-based IoT applications.
Conclusion

QoS 1 is the most suitable option for water level monitoring because it ensures reliable delivery of critical alerts while maintaining efficient network and power usage.
